{
  "doc_id": "17708",
  "text": "For the general population, diet is the main source of exposure to Co and it is readily absorbed from the small intestine [CITATION_1] 76] . Most of the consumed Co is excreted in the urine and the little that is retained is mainly in the liver and kidneys [CITATION_2] . Under physiological conditions, this element is mostly accumulated in the liver, kidneys, heart, and spleen, while minimum concentrations are found in the blood serum and tissues of the brain and pancreas [CITATION_3] . Molecular details of the mode of Co uptake into cells are not well known [76, [CITATION_4] . However, it is likely that it is transported into the cells by broad-specificity divalent metal transporters [CITATION_5] . It has been shown that P2X7, a transmembrane ionotropic receptor, is involved in the uptake of divalent cations and Co [CITATION_6] . In the same way, a protein named divalent metal transporter 1 (DMT1) has been shown to have a broad substrate specificity favouring divalent metals including Co 2+ [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . Additionally, the cellular uptake of Co may be mediated both by active transport ion pumps (i.e., Ca 2+/ Mg 2+ ATPase and Na + /K + ATPase) and endocytosis [CITATION_10] .",
